Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A lunatic asylum where young people are supposed to meet today.
A crypt chapel, where now is excavated for the S Bahn tunnel.
Leisure gardeners cultivate the land once owned by farmers.
The oldest official map of Munich brings exciting stories to light.
It is annoying when maps are not up to date.
Everyone knows this, who had to get excited, because the car, Navi instead of a bypass road indicated a green meadow.
The historical maps of the digital Bavaria, Atlases, an offer of the geoportal Bavaria of the state government, are anything but topical - but for this very reason very informative.
Especially if you compare them with current online cards.
Then it becomes clear how cities and municipalities in the distribution area of the Münchner Merkur have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bavarian Atlas is a patchwork quilt that is not immediately recognizable as such.
More detailed maps, so-called original maps, were incorporated into the large overview map for cities and municipalities.
These arose according to the Bavarian Surveying Administration between 1810 and 1864 and originate from the first survey of Bavaria.
Your client: Napoleon.
The French army leader occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and ordered a topographical survey of Bavaria - of course for military purposes.
Even if the French troops finally withdrew with the peace of Lunéville of 9 February 1801: It was the current neighbours who created the idea of a comprehensive map of Bavaria.
Elector Max IV Joseph pushed the project further, founded the "Topographic Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The original position sheet for Munich dates from the year 1856 and, like all the others, can be found on the website of the Bayerische Landesbibliothek.
The comparison between the past and the present is most impressive in the case of the state capital.
The city expanded in all directions and grew together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which appears relatively isolated in the map of 1856.
Sendling was incorporated as a district of Munich 21 years after the map was drawn up, i.e. in 1877.
Today Untersendling is located in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendling are concentrated around 1856 along today ’ s Plinganserstraße, which was named after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the 1705 uprising of Bavarian farmers against Austria, only in 1878.
Where today is the Westpark, you can see nothing but fields - at first glance: When zooming in, a smaller map appears with dozens of lines and numbers: hand-numbered hallway pieces from the so-called "original photograph" from which the property tax was derived.
Small parcels of land are no longer occupied by farmers, but by allotment gardeners of the "Land in Sonne" complex.
A large green area appears north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, site of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was actually a meadow in the 19th century - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map provides an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the original position sheet you can read in the area of the today's district Au, Haidhausen not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the hill "Auf der Lüften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstraße people were once locked up with delusions.
There in 1858 / 59 the Munich circle "mental asylum" on the Auer air "was created.
From 1872, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden, the psychiatrist associated with the death of King Ludwig II, directed the institution.
"He was progressive for his time and ended, for example, the chains of the so-called lunatics.
He also forbade the staff to use violence against the inmates, "says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Haidhausen Museum, who dealt with the institution for an exhibition.
At first there was room for 280 patients, but later it was extended to 500.
At some point, even this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the Kreisirrenanstalt in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, it has been home to Isar ’ s Amper Hospital in Munich, one of the largest psychiatry centres in Germany.
Young people now meet in the Munich Salesianum on the grounds of the former Au Institute.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth hostel with training facilities.
To the west lies the soccer field of TSV München Ost, to the east residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's house "Casa Don Bosco" was built - architecturally based on the original building of the mental institution, which had been destroyed in World War II by bomb attacks.
The Marienplatz was listed as "Haupt Platz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War brought a decisive change to the heart of Munich.
In December 1944, Allied bombs tore many holes in the city centre.
A large one remained until today - at the Marienhof.
The English Institute, small business premises and a crypt chapel from the Middle Ages once stood at the Marienhof, where these days the preparatory work and on 5 April 2017 the groundbreaking ceremony for the second S-Bahn main line will take place.
With the slider you can compare the old map of Munich with the aerial view of today - and fill up the hole at Marienhof.
Civil Rights Group publishes travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color who travel to Missouri because of the state ’ s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is due to take effect by 28 August 2017, calls on afro, American travelers, visitors and Missouri travelers to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling through the state, as a number of questionable, race-based incidents have occurred and been noted across the state recently," the group said.
A recent Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as state law enforcement agencies disproportionately targeting minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"They have violations of civil rights that happen to people.
They are stopped because of their skin color, they are beaten up or killed, "the President of the Missouri NAACP, Rod Chapel, told the Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints in such a frequency that we have not heard."
It is the first such warning issued by the Organization for a State in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist offenses against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances at the beginning of the year, having run out of gasoline during his state tour, and having been taken into custody by the Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The Council also points to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General ’ s Office showing that black car drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than whites.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and inform their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People must be ready whether they bring bail money or let their relatives know that they are travelling through the state."
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI ’ s hate crime reporting program, ranking the state 16th in the country in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri ’ s law that would make it more difficult to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona following the adoption by states of immigration laws requiring local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department to other countries, but recently interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
