Now Trump ’ s White House Goes to the Statue of Liberty
The safest sign of regime change is when they begin to attack the statues.
Americans value them as much as anyone else – hence the carefully orchestrated fall of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad ’ s Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of Trump ’ s key ideologues, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated argument with CNN ’ s Jim Acosta over the president ’ s proposals to drastically limit legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller did not attack the statue itself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty ’ s imitators would have lynched him if he had done so.
But he attacked its meaning, and in particular the meaning attributed to it when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument.
When Miller insulted Acosta, "I don't want to go into a complete thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that enlightens the world.
The poem to which you refer, which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty. "
Miller is right, but as he put it, it is not really history.
It is about the contemporary resonance to the stirring words of Lazarus, the only ones in which a state invites not only some old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Your tired, your poor, / your oppressed masses who long to breathe freely / the miserable waste of your rich coasts."
There was never a time when the "miserable waste" was better visible on our screens.
Miller did not engage in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump ’ s US.
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural debate: it is indeed a conflict over the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who campaigned for her words to be placed at the grassroots after her death - knew very well that they were carrying out a highly political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the connections between French and American Republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classical pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: In her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has received a voice.
And she gives herself a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The connection between the poem and the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the people of the right wing wanted to change it back a long time.
The big screamer Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty does not invite anyone, but rather is an early neoconservative who brings the American flame into the deranged world: "Lady Liberty is moving forward.
It is to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch should not illuminate the way to the United States. "
Limbaugh has come across something quite unusual here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of perception.
The great fanciful act of Lazarus was to see it as it was seen by the weary, miserable, but hopeful men after long and often terrible voyages on the decks of ships.
It is literally about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome that they must hear.
And that, of course, is not the perspective Miller and Trump ever want to recognize.
Their torch is not meant to illuminate the path, but to ignite the hatred that is their only source of power.
