Blocking critics on Facebook: Don ’ t apply for public office if you can ’ t stand voter incitement
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it didn ’ t take long for newspapers to beat him for everything, from domestic politics to his political principles.
He scolded at the criticism, for sure.
But he has not silenced his critics.
Because in 1783 Washington said: "Freedom of speech can be taken away - and, dumb and dumb, we are led like sheep to slaughter."
That brings me to Maryland to Governor Larry Hogan, who must work to be more like Washington.
Hogan ’ s employees have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have voiced their opinions on its official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him about it earlier this week.
The governor ’ s staff dismissed the suit as frivolous, and the online commentary was full of a backlash with “So what? ”.
“It ’ s just Facebook, ” many people said.
But it is important.
And it ’ s especially important if it ’ s a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state that is astonishingly popular.
It has the second highest approval of the 50 governors of the nation.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in the governance of his state and strict adherence to the principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as the primary means of connecting with his voters and playfully debuting his hairless head after chemotherapy on his side.
Therefore, the blocking of people who come on the governor's side - which is a public forum that is called official and of employees who are paid public tax, dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan ’ s spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor ’ s actions, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than a moderation.
But it is too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people wielding the whip online.
The post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are only real people who speak to their elected leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur, and a pastor, not trolls.
They all said that their comments were respectful, thoughtful and not profane.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md., was not hateful, but she asked about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other news," she wrote in the commentary section of the news program "The Post."
"I also do not appreciate this idea, if a number of people take a stand on the same subject, then they are rather disregarded by some as a so-called collective effort and not recognized as a large group of affected citizens".
What the governor's staff called a "concentrated spam attack," others would probably call an "intercession."
Facebook ’ s “era ” makes it easy to crop a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It is much cleaner than it was in the past to do the same thing by sending employees to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials or arrest and silence demonstrators.
But that is exactly what is happening digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for insulting Facebook and other social media outlets.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked by his Twitter ’ s feed.
