Poverty and death in the Indonesian goldland
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she does not use a stove.
She even seldom uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai regency in the troubled Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually puts a sweet potato - locally referred to as "nota" - directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and devoured with eager, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also does her daily work, such as washing clothes with murky water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband ’ s four wives, no fields were assigned to her.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most villagers are unemployed, and many drink heavily, and there are soldiers here.
"Nobody dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m.," she says.
It is a rare insight into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was admitted to Indonesia after a controversial referendum in 1969, when only 1,026 elders were to vote by a public handshake before the occupying forces.
An existing anti-Dutch independence movement quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which controls the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea covering the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is desolate. It includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire and then a 5-hour morning car ride.
There is no public transport.
The town of about 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated iron roofs, which have been transformed by rust into various yellow-brown tones.
Very few Indonesians have made their way here, let alone journalists and practically no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There have also been other changes.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes," says Degei, pointing to her lively, hand-woven turban, dark shirt and light skirt.
"We used to have only leaves on our bodies."
Papua is Indonesia ’ s poorest province, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line and some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia ’ s gold country.
The world ’ s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix ’ s Freeport McMoran, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with 153,000 inhabitants.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
Papua also has an estimated USD 78 billion in timber resources.
But these riches are a source of misery for Papua, ensuring that Indonesia ’ s powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
An investigation in the New York Times in 2005 reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly 20 million US dollars between 1998 and 2004, including up to 150,000 US dollars to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass-killings in Papua ’ s tribal highlands in the 1970 ’ s became a genocide according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful demonstrators last year.
"We will lose everything," says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities of the previous year, such as unlawful executions and torture - rape and electric shocks are particularly popular, according to another report - and the brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to count the number of victims, as incidents happen every week," says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia, a researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have strengthened as Papua's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The population of 3.5 million inhabitants of the province is 83% Christian, but the demographic development is changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warung, canteens sell fried chicken and gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people are fighting to keep up.
“Migrants have started to sell chickens and vegetables at the traditional market cheaper than the local Papua, ” says Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai, a local who moved to work in the provincial capital of Jayapura.
"It has cost the indigenous Papuans - the mama- [the women] of Papua - their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised during his 2014 election campaign to address the inequalities and violations of rights in Papua.
The former carpenter secured 27 of the 29 districts of Papua - including Paniai - on the way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel cheated.
“Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored, ” You said.
Indeed, just two months after Jokowi ’ s inauguration in October, Paniai suffered a low.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children was outside singing Christmas carols in front of a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers broke through the darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offence at their tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to the local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers who had drunk chased and beat the group with their rifle butts, saying victims and witnesses.
Then one of the soldiers fired into a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the building of the nearby government commission was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
Approximately 1,000 young Papua men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and military command centre to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita ’ s dance – running in circles and imitating a birdsong – of Papua ’ s Mee Pago ’ s tribe.
Some demonstrators began hurling stones at police and military stations.
When the atmosphere was heated, an order was sent to the soldiers via an internal radio: "If the masses resist more than three times, they shoot them dead," says an official document of TIME, which was not released to the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of Kego Koto ’ s Enarotali neighborhood, saw the threat and called for calm, urging the crowd to return home.
Nobody was in the mood to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist," he said TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who fired, but says that the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, many shots were fired," he adds.
The local man Alfius Youw was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shootings.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," said Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, has only one name, the TIME in a gloomy mood.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
The chief inspector of the Papua Police, Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers only wanted to "secure" her station because she was being attacked.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," said Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, spokesman for the Papua Police, in 2015.
"It's about life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young demonstrators were killed and many more injured.
The news of the killings only came to Jakarta 'filtered' on the following day.
For three weeks Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, in which he expressed sympathy for the families of the victims and swore to address the historical grievances in Papua.
"I want this case to be resolved immediately so that it will not happen again in the future," he said.
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he was establishing an out-of-court mechanism to resolve historic human rights violations.
But the excuses began almost immediately.
"Most injuries occurred a long time ago.
Some were in the 90's and early 2000's.
The point is that we are committed to tackling these violations, but there are processes that need to be followed, "he said.
Then Wiranto made a retreat when he spoke to TIME in Jakarta on June 5, saying he had no plans to set up a complaint mechanism in Papua.
Instead, “everything is regulated by law, ” he said.
Wiranto, whom the UN has indicted for "crimes against humanity" that claimed more than 1,000 lives in East Timor's bloody 1999 independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
Paniai victims ’ families accepted such claims with grim incredulity.
“I have been interviewed four times in the last three years, but there has been no progress, ” says Yohanes.
"I'm tired."
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I am afraid of being arrested by the military, I am afraid of being shot."
His brother Yacobus repeated the view that the people of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by the military after helping bury four of the victims.
"After I buried the bodies, the military searched for me," he says.
The shootings have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot at villagers in Paniai ’ s Deiyai neighborhood.
