The man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Excited villagers protested in front of the company's location office.
The police said that the villagers threw stones at officers who responded by firing warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) began shooting at the crowd and killing one.
"We were so panicked, we are afraid that there will be revenge," says 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed how the injured were brought in quickly, according to the TIME.
"I hid in my house for two days."
The Deiyai Parliament has called for the officers involved to be held accountable and for the mobile police brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a source of concern for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development strengthens the dissatisfaction of the tribesmen Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal, who live in the green highlands of Papua.
Many joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), the rebel army, which claims to defend the rights of Papua by launching sporadic attacks and kidnappings of Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained in Paniai in recent years on the pretext of 'safeguarding national sovereignty'.
Some never show up again.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is known as "a tragic, forgotten place".
Poverty increases dissatisfaction.
The little rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is also out of reach.
People here grow everything they eat: especially nota and fruit and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the job of women, who can work four or five fields of sweet potatoes each.
They keep most of the harvest for the family, while the rest is sold at the local market.
Ten pieces of nota cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic disparities have grown between indigenous Papua and the new migrants who have arrived in large numbers since the opening of new routes to Nabire airport.
The few jobs that exist in the region tend to go to the better-educated and wealthier migrants.
Papua rarely have the capital or skills to run their own competitive businesses.
"The young people are not interested in staying in the village... because there are no jobs or money," says John Gobai, chairman of the tribal council of Paniai.
Isolation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
Moreover, restrictions on reporting by international media remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for lack of coordination with related institutions, although they were given the rare permission to film.
According to Phelim Kine, Asia ’ s deputy director of Human Rights Watch, Jokowi ’ s campaign ’ s promises to lift reporting restrictions to promote transparency and development have not been realized.
"There are new dangers for foreign journalists trying to report on Indonesia's troubled easternmost provinces of Papua and West Papua: visa refusal and a blacklist," he said in a statement.
Lack of press control means that international pressure on the Indonesian government remains largely limited to Papua ’ s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific states - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate the "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Paniai shootings.
The same countries have historically supported the OPM.
The spokesman for the Indonesian Foreign Ministry, Arrmanatha Nasir, rejected the group's accusations and told journalists in Jakarta: "In Indonesia there is still a democratic system and there are free media, so it is difficult to cover up the evidence of human rights cases."
Local people want more foreign governments to take note.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Human Rights Ambassador Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals broke their silence and harassed him, "We want freedom," according to a source that also attended the meeting but wants to remain anonymous.
Indonesia has another presidential election in 2019, but Papua say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
“Jokowi is a person with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people who are involved in the Paniai, ” says Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the Paniai people, apart from living under the constant threat of a predatory military, are in poor education and health services.
