The preservation of the oldest building in the village has been made a matter of concern to the friends and sponsors of Tumlingen.
Walter Martini emphasizes: "It is a unique village gem".
In the year 1267, the St. Hilarius Chapel was first mentioned in a document of Württemberg: Count Hermann von Sulz sold "the hill with the parish church of Tumlingen and the bailiwick on it" to Magister Eberhard von Horb and to his brother Dietrich for 20 Marks silver.
According to the wording of the document, in addition to the former parish church, there was also a manorial court on the Tumlinger Berg to which the church or patronage right belonged and not the other way around.
People also lived there.
As can be seen from the description of the Freudenstadt Upper Office from 1858, the "mountain" was next to the lower village and the upper village, which can still be seen in the townscape of Tumlingen, the third, the lordly settlement centre of the village.
Old maps from around the year 1600 confirm these historical facts.
The patronage right originated from the early medieval proper church right.
A lord, who built a church, furnished it and occupied it with a priest, continued to be the owner of this church and could also inherit it.
Associated with this was the right to appoint a pastor or to propose a new pastor to the bishop.
There were three altars in the church and two bells on the tower.
The larger of the two burst at Christmas 1673.
The newly purchased bell sounded for the first time in 1692, but had to be delivered later in the Second World War in 1942.
In the 30-year war (1616-1648) the windows were broken and the bell ropes stolen.
The roof was leaking.
In 1796 French troops camped near the church.
They broke out the pulpit and church chairs and used them as firewood.
Remains of the church threatened to collapse in 1809.
Until 1869, the cemetery was also the final resting place of the dead from Hörschweiler.
In 1823 the cemetery was extended and the Hilariuskirche was demolished.
Only the church steeple was left standing.
On New Year's Eve 1834 a storm split the steeple and half collapsed.
To prevent an accident, the tower was demolished.
Only the still existing tower dwarf remained as a witness of the 750 years old church history.
Today Horst Kallenberger and Rolf Dieter Wasem of the "Schaffigen Pensioners", successor of Dieter Dockhorn, maintain the Hilarius plant.
On Sunday, 16 July, the Friends and Sponsors of Tumlingen invite you to the sixth Serenade at the old cemetery St. Hilariuskapelle.
It will be designed by the Kepler Gymnasium Freudenstadt combo and with contributions by Kurt Kübler and Reinhold Matteis.
Hartmut Romann speaks the closing words.
The programme will start at 4.30 p.m.
Admission is from 15.30 clock.
At the end of the serenade there is a drink in front of the cemetery.
“Enjoy a summer evening under the shade of old trees and with the wide view over meadows to the forest ”, the organizers point out the fantastic view.
The Serenade only takes place in dry weather.
The organizers hope for many supporters for the preservation of the historic St. Hilarius, which is important for Tumlingen and Hörschweiler.
The friends and sponsors of Tumlingen feel particularly committed to the care of local history, as confirmed by Serenade, the organizer Walter Martini.
