New results of Swedish asylum seeker evaluation tests published
The latest results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have undergone a new method of medical evaluation of their age, show that more than 80% of those tested are older than 18, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started conducting the tests last year.
During the asylum procedure, they are to make the age assessment more accurate after the Swedish Migration Board (Migrationsverket) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent out 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty per cent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 years or older."
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under 18 years of age".
The tests are only carried out in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson from the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past few months.
"We don't see much difference in the statistics of the past months, the numbers are pretty constant," he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases in which the person is judged to be over the age of 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker has lied about his or her age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said that there were 442 cases that "suggest that the person examined is 18 years or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it stated that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that he would be 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age evaluation, where x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI are taken, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
One skeptic is the Karolinska institute ’ s endocrinologist Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing people ’ s biological maturity to see if they passed through puberty sooner or later than usual.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don ’ t think the type of measurement should be used.
Assessing biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say it for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can, "he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson from the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is when the person is just under 18, in this case about 10 percent. "
