NHS (The National Health Service) to prescribe controversial HIV-related drug to 10,000 people
Patients will have access to "transformative" HIV prevention treatment as of September, following a battle before the High Court against NHS funding.
NHS England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 per cent, is now being provided by the health service through a first three years ’ study for an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the process after the Court of Appeal last year upheld a Supreme Court ruling that the NHS had the power to pay for the PrEP, despite claims that local authorities should fund it.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed by NHS England ’ s Simon Stevens as an “important new intervention, ” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called it a“ defining moment. ”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to enable people to register, and more will follow in October, before being rolled out across the UK in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a sequence of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that just enough drugs are present in a person ’ s body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken two hours before sexual intercourse every day or so.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals and people with HIV positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
In clinics, appropriate participants are identified who agree with the study, including men, women, transgenders and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a family doctor can also register for a possible participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The program will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract for the delivery of the drugs this week following an international competitive procurement.
The aim of the study is to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on a large-scale, targeted use, uptake and implementation.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and overtake the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in the more than three decades of sustained progress in addressing one of the greatest health challenges facing mankind. "
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive of NAT (National Aids Trust), said: "This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted at needy and vulnerable people, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September onwards, people at high HIV risk will have access to this NHS "funded trial" in England to develop a new instrument that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, leading to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement. "
Ian Green, Chairman of the Board of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now must be for the study to be carried out quickly across the country and for no one at risk of HIV to be left behind.
Now that the PrEP test medicine has been procured, we are well on the way to protecting more than 10,000 people infected with HIV. "
Sharon Hodgson, Shadow Health Minister, said: "The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and slow implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and can stop transmission of this life-changing infection.
This experiment brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that this study is carried out as quickly as possible throughout the country in order to protect people infected with HIV and to help bring us one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society '.
