Brothers Fight for a 500 Million U.S. Dollars Real Estate Empire
Four decades after her Italian family founded the dynasty, two brothers are in conflict over one of Victoria ’ s largest real-estate empires, worth more than $500 million.
Former director of the Carlton Football ’ s Club and developer Colin De Lutis lives in a villa in Toorak, just three doors from his younger brother Paul, who has taken him to the Supreme Court to see how their property and business assets should be divided.
Paul has wanted to withdraw from the family business since 2014, but a heated argument over the separation is taking place in the Supreme Court.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 38 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, accumulated since the family bought a store on Smith Street, Collingwood, in 1973.
There the Westco family founded Jeans and grew to a chain of 160 retail stores.
It was sold in 1999 for 85 million US dollars.
This money was invested in real estate, and De Lutis ’ portfolio now includes offices in the city centre, the development areas of Brunswick and Sorrento, the apartments in Gold Coast and Mt Buller, and shopping centres in the suburbs.
Following an agreement with her late father, Colin - described by Paul as "the main operator and the dominant personality" in the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets and Paul about one-third.
One court record states that this means that Colin has property worth $316 million and Paul $176 million.
The division of real estate and cash has been a problem for Paul.
"Colin's proposed allocations left him with what I thought were the best objects," he wrote in a first affidavit in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed conciliations, the first hearing of the Supreme Court took place.
The brothers now also fight for control of the existing business - from which Colin, as Paul claims, has excluded him.
Colin argues that this is not true, but accuses Paul of incompetently managing some possessions.
