"My Italian heritage dictates that the family is the most important priority," he wrote.
Costs are rising in the case, with hundreds of pages containing affiliates, e-mails and reports from companies including Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer, and with leading lawyers including Allan Myers, QC, and law firms held by both sides.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were Italian immigrants who ran dairy bars and delicatessens from the late 1950s and bought a shop in Brunswick in the early 1970s.
They used security to buy Collingwood ’ s property, where Colin opened the family ’ s first denim store.
Colin says he started Westco there when he was "in my last years of high school, when Paul was a young child (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to pass on their property amicably to their sons.
