Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of De Lutis ’ s corporate group, with Colin claiming that Mark was paid $10 million and Luke $26 million upon leaving the company.
Both Luke and Mark, Paul says, "have become embittered about the conditions of their financial separation."
Colin has held back a great deal, though he was a former AFL executive board member and, following a 2015 biography of Eddie McGuire, the television star ’ s best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul De Lutis and their attorneys.
Only Colin answered by SMS to say "I really can't say much" because the case was before the courts.
"It is very, very sad that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and to drag our surname through the courts," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote to the court that he had tried to meet his brother ’ s demands.
"Our father wouldn't have wanted Paul and I to end up in our current quarrel," he said, adding that he was "still hoping for a solution."
On Friday, that hope seemed to be over.
"Our case will be resolved by the courts in the near future," wrote Colin.
Trump ’ s new chief of staff plans to limit the president ’ s media abstinence.
Others have tried and failed.
