Antarctica: Giant iceberg floating in Antarctica
In the West Antarctic, a gigantic iceberg the size of Berlin has separated from the shelf ice.
This was reported by Bremerhaven ’ s Alfredo Wegener, Institute for Polar and Marine Research, on Wednesday.
The giant, weighing over a trillion tons and measuring 5,800 square kilometres, is now drifting northwards and will probably take two or three years to melt.
With a length of 175 kilometres and a width of up to 50 kilometres, it is one of the largest ice giants recorded by researchers over the past three decades.
It does not pose a danger to people.
According to researchers, the extent to which climate change played a role in the collapse of the iceberg is unclear.
Altogether, however, there has been a series of unusual collapses of ice shelves in the region for about 30 years, writes the US Research Center for Snow and Ice (NSIDC) in a factual background.
According to many researchers, this could be related to global warming.
The now broken colossus has been part of the Larsen ’ C ’ Ice Shelf.
Ice shelves swim on the sea and are fed by large glaciers.
It grows further and further into the sea and breaks up regularly.
It is located south of South America at the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula.
North of this shelf ice, the balance between growing and breaking was disturbed a few years ago.
A complete shelf ice has fallen apart there, writes AWI researcher Daniela Jansen.
There is reason to believe that the Larsen ’ C ’ shelf ice is also in danger, because the front edge has never retreated as far as it is now.
In addition, the ice plate is under tension and could disintegrate if a piece breaks off at a crux.
Melting of ice shelves and icebergs does not raise the sea level, as they float on the water and displace as much water as is produced after melting.
However, the loss of the ice shelf means that the glaciers flow directly into the sea and can drain away much faster than before.
This could possibly raise the sea level, but only to a limited extent, writes the British research project to observe Antarctica (Midas).
According to AWI, the Larsen ’ C ’ shelf ice is the fourth largest shelf ice in Antarctica, measuring almost 50,000 square kilometres.
At the transition from the mainland it is up to 700 meters thick, at the leading edge to the free ocean about 200 meters.
There it breaks off regularly.
"Although it is a natural event and we are not aware of any direct link to climate change, the ice sheet is now in a more vulnerable position," said Swansea University's Martin O'Leary.
"This is the widest retreat since the beginning of the records," he confirmed.
According to his colleague, Adrian Luckman, there is a dispute among scientists as to whether the Larsen “C ” ice shelf will grow again or decline in the long term and possibly collapse, adding:“ Our models say it will be less stable. ”
But this development will take decades.
Even if these researchers do not attribute the collapse of this gigantic iceberg to climate change, many ice shelves on the Antarctic Peninsula have disintegrated in recent decades.
This long tip of Antarctica extends towards South America.
According to data from the British Antarctic Survey, the ice sheet on the Antarctic Peninsula has fallen by 28,000 square kilometres since the 1950s.
The temperature rise contributed to the decline.
The Antarctic Peninsula has warmed up by around three degrees in the past 50 years, making it one of the areas where the temperature rises the fastest.
