Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid his enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
Researchers have now discovered that the first findings of the incredible rhino of a Canadian miner have been so well received that experts have described it as the "Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs".
It was so well preserved that they could even find that its scaly skin was of reddish brown - and they said it had some of a "troubled past".
The report in the journal "Current Biology" described him as "the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaurs in the world".
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly well preserved condition has astounded researchers who describe it as "truly remarkable"
According to National Geographic reports, the armored herbivore is the best preserved fossil of its kind.
It was found by Shawn Funk when he was digging at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He encountered something that seemed out of place from the surrounding rock, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil discovered by him was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal within the 2,500 pound (1,100 kg) lump of earth.
After all this hard work, the finished result is now ready to be revealed.
"If you just blink your eyes a little, you could almost believe that it has slept", said the lead author Caleb Brown, scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature can be seen.
"It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaurs" - the Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs. "
Researchers have found that this herbivore, although covered in armor and resembling a walking armor, was probably threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used a red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a screening technique known as anti-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to mingle better with its surroundings and avoid its enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110 million-year-old creature from the nodosaur family made headlines for the first time in May and can now be seen in the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers have now studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that has spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering it.
The amazing preservation of the specimen enabled Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor over his body.
They discovered Countershading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, meaning that the creature's top was darker than its bottom.
Although countershading is common, the results are surprising, as the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of today ’ s animals.
It suggests that the dinosaur was hunted by enough pressure from carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution favored the concealment of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most contemporary animals that use countershading - think of deer, zebras, or armadillos - are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey, signaling that this nodosaur has been subjected to a real struggle for survival.
"Strong predator behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaurs must have been," Brown said.
The chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the skin of the dinosaur was red-brown.
Scientists continue to examine the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it has eaten as its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it got into a river and was driven out into the sea, where it sank on its back to the seabed.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as southern Florida today, and rivers and oceans probably spread much further inland than they are today.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, but also retains three dimensions and retains the original form of the animal," Brown said.
"The result is that the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous period.
You don't need to use much imagination to reconstruct it. If you just squint a little with your eyes, you might almost believe he is asleep. "
The Cretaceous period was a time when huge theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, crossed the earth.
Although the king of them, the Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years after Borealopelta, the armored dinosaur was hunted by some of its fearsome ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot, six-ton monster.
The scientists, whose latest findings are published in the journal Current Biology, believe that after death Borealopelta sank into the sea and was mummified in the mud.
The creature was found by Shawn Funk when he was digging at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum, it is the best preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, and is complete from muzzle to hip.
The creatures were on average about 18 feet long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds.
It contained two 20 inches long spikes sticking out from his shoulders.
The researchers believe that the armored herbivore was washed through Western Canada until a flooded river flooded it into the open sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur kept his armor in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the skin remains still cover bumpy armor plates along the dinosaur
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, such a level of preservation is as' rare as a lottery win.
The more I look at it, the more confusing it becomes.
Fossilized remains of the skin still cover the bumpy armor plates, which carry the skull of the animal.
His right forefoot is at his side, his five fingers spread upward.
I can count the scales at his sole '.
