Only a small number of test customers can use the new service.
And only on ICE 915 Dortmund, Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart, Essen.
Further train numbers on the same route have not yet been activated.
How did one activist learn the answer to the question: "Whose Streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just a day after she arrived in New York City, the St. Louis-born sat on the bed of an Airbnb ’ apartment she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled upon a post from someone in high school.
"The police have just killed an 18-year-old child, and it is still on the street," it said.
Confused, as no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the @ TheePharoah handle was constantly retweeted on their timeline.
The St. Louis rapper was about to tweet the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18 year-old boy killed by a white cop in Ferguson, Mo., live.
He posted a picture of Brown ’ s lifeless body, which was stretched out on the street and would stay there for four hours.
"That's wild," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to them and their community.
She put down her phone to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were photos of the police band and people shouting, and of a man claiming to be Brown's father carrying a sign reading, "Ferguson's police just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live feed in which a policeman stood in front of a group of demonstrators with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another policeman unlocked his rifle and shouted, "I'll kill you... animals all."
"This is not usual," recalled Ferrell.
"This is not the kind of murder we have become accustomed to and which we can call typical."
At that moment I felt chills.
I was angry and cried. "
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father ’ s house and decided that they would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson in the following three years is the subject of a new documentary film, "Whose Streets?", in cinemas from the 11th
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience that exists from the point of view of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell went to Ferguson with her daughter, who wore a floral dress and a fitting crown, the two discussed a conversation they had countless times before that morning "about the black experience and the black condition".
"You remember how I taught you, when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she remembered what she said.
"We are now going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that was not right.
I couldn ’ t take them with me, ” Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a climax of... what happened in the past.
She must know it and see it and be raised in it.
It must be well developed, not only activism and organization, but also know the different layers of the black experience and the black constitution and what we must do to become free, to liberate ourselves.
Even if I am lucky enough to give her an experience in which she personally experiences no blatant racism, she is no different from the next black woman, a child.
I feel I would do her a disservice in keeping her away from it. "
The first stop, when they arrived in Ferguson, was on South Florissant Road, a place across from the police department, which became a camp area as the activists waited for the possible non-indictment of Officer Darren Wilson.
There Ferrell and her daughter joined a local business owner who had lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to demonstrators.
Slowly a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism has totally changed since August 9," she said, noting that while a student at the University of Missouri, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
Everything has come. "
Weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film ’ s co-directors.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado, Farrar, just wanted to "document" what was happening.
One question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document or are you trying to find a story you can exploit?"
This skepticism was fueled by countless cases of people, often whites, in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan stated in a recent interview, "We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson did not center their voices, and we wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had already worked with the then co-director Damon Davis, an artist from the field known for his activism around Death Row.
His engagement brought Ferrell closer to the project, and along with six other locals followed the Whose Streets? team in the years following Brown ’ s execution.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or talks to us. We're talking," Davis said.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people are portrayed, because that's how I will be portrayed."
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement was "not a Messiah, a leader, but a community coming together," Folayan said - she proved to be the most open participant in the film.
As a result, documents from "Whose Streets?" show surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, how she falls in love and marries her wife.
"I felt like naked," Ferrell said, laughing when she first saw the finished product.
"But I have understood that there must be a certain vulnerability in this work and in the humanization of black people."
Furthermore, Ferrell ’ s story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black Life movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who coined the film "BlacklivesMatter" in social media after the killing of the black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012, identify themselves as gay.
"Black gay women in leadership positions have supported the movement as a whole," Ferrell said, "and that is why we are constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women must bear the brunt of everything. "
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really being maintained by black women and many black women."
She insists, however, that "this is not an affirmative type of action" in which Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who shook up this energy," she said.
"It is no coincidence, although she was at the forefront, because there is so much at stake in a life at these crossroads as a black, gay woman.
You can feel their energy through the screen. "
The Ferguson news cameras have long since disappeared, but the racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is on probation for 2 ½ years for blocking a highway at a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls home: "A chaos".
Yet she clings to a song, and she has been devoted to that memory ever since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains. "
