Creating a Comic-strip Novel: A Castle in the History of England
In his more recent past, the little Scotney Castle was featured in a squeeze of a music video and was a loophole for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney has lived through 700 years of turbulent history from his cosy home in Kent ’ s Bewl River valley, and has now become the inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes, a mophaired Yorkshire man with a penchant for historical documents.
"I find it so beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years," he says wistfully.
"What a personal relationship to hold this letter in my hand."
'A Castle in England 'covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Age of Edward and documents the families who lived in Scotney. Each story is illustrated by a different, emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It is not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: he wrote 'Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories' in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
“I only responded to the thumb print on the page of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700 ’ s who worked for the Jacobins, ” he says.
"This is his thumb print!
And letters always smell of smoke, because at that time a fire was lit because of the light.
For someone who lives 300 years later, the smell has an effect as if it were part of it.
Oh, I love archives! "
For someone so beaten up with old papers that he is supported by the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and has lived in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest: I overrated my welcome a bit"), all this seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent its days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, reviewing the archives and studying the many treasures and curiosities of the castle, such as the mounted hyena heads on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries in the ditch.
He walked through the grounds and ruins of the old castle and talked to landscape conservators, gardeners and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then, at night, he drank "Whiskey and began to write".
The intimate history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained full access in 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, employees were just beginning to take care of the archive, which he described as "hundreds of years in which aristocrats said," Oh, throw it in the attic. "
Diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, maps depicting who owned what: “You might think that land conflicts would be boring, ” says Rhodes,“ but there was a birch tree that two families fought over.
Guys, let everything go its way! "
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to immerse themselves in English history on a broader basis, including 'The Labourer', which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the peasant revolt of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot that occurred in the castle in 1380 in this book entitled 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex'," says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising started in this area and I thought an uprising was a good start.
Perhaps the two are connected? "
Other stories are firmly rooted in the history of the castle - such as' The Priest ', which tells the story of the Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler', which depicts the 18th century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery made years later when his coffin was unearthed).
The Darrell's are Rhodes' favourite family of Scotney: "The gentlemen seemed to be quite crooks, always running into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Other generations of Darrell ’ s men solved their debt crises by marrying wealthy old women – I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking boys with a talent for courting heiresses. ”
After the end of his assignment at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experience
He has spent two weeks in the wilderness of Finland writing a novel about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th century sanatorium, which has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
It was like, "Oh, now I have to deal with the damn life again."
