Afghan democracy depends on the political role of women, says UN
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, play a role, said the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, acting head of the UN mission, said hundreds of women will stand in the provincial council elections, three women will stand in the role of vice-president and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters will be women.
"The role of women cannot be overestimated," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are involved in all parts of the election process.
Afghan elections for the Provincial Council and presidential elections will be held on 5 April.
The Taliban have issued threats against an election process, which coincide with the transition from international hostilities to an advisory role.
This year, for the first time, the elections will move power peacefully from one democratically elected government to another.
Haysom said a strong role for women will reinforce Afghanistan's democratic success.
The Afghan Independent Electoral Commission reports that 1.2 million women out of a total of 3.6 million registered voters are registered.
