GMB ’ s concern about investment in McVitie ’ s Glasgow factory
A union wants to convince managers of biscuit manufacturer McVitie of their long-term commitment to production at their Glasgow plant.
GMB Scotland said the company had been silent about the future of investments at Tollcross ’ s site.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which produces Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits, among other products.
McVities owner Pladis said he has invested more than £5 million in recent years.
He added that employees and union representatives would be "first to know" when their activities would change.
In a letter to the company's branch manager, GMB invited Scotland McVitie's to "express concerns that funding for the modernisation of production lines will not be advanced".
GMB ’ s senior organizer, Drew Duffy, said: “The fact that we are unable to gain clarity from the general site manager about the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross deeply affects our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily concentrated in the local community and Greater Glasgow, an important pillar of decent employment in an area with high unemployment and social deprivation.
Therefore, from the perspective of jobs, wages and prosperity, and in the context of Brexit, rising living costs and chronic production decline, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a flourishing production presence at McVitie ".
A Pladis spokesperson said: "The branch manager at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday and the company will respond directly as we appreciate the continued engagement with employees and union representatives.
Two months ago we had a regular meeting with staff and GMB representatives at Tollcross, where some questions were discussed openly.
We discussed with the employees that, like all companies operating in a highly competitive and uncertain economic climate, we constantly review our business - and this applies to all our business units and locations - in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years, we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise the heritage of Tollcross as a production site. If our operations at the site change, the employees and their union representatives will be the first to know. "
