Interview: "Cathedral sparrows" Report relieves Pope George Ratzinger "
The Regensburger Domspatzen "Report on Abuse Cases" exonerates Pope Georg Ratzinger.
This is the opinion of author and historian Michael Hesemann.
The final report to the abuse scandal with the Regensburger Domspatzen provides further discussions.
Christian Weisnder, speaker of the reform movement "We are Church", declared after publication to the German press "Agency", he expected an apology from the former Regensburg bishop and today's Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller as well as from the cathedral music director Georg Ratzinger, the 93 year old brother of the emeritus Pope Benedict XVI.
It would be of great benefit to the prestige of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger were to express their deep regret at their own omissions or their then incorrect assessment of events.
The Vatican newspaper "Osservatore Romano", on the other hand, criticised the "double standards" applied to the reporting of violence against the cathedral sparrows.
Regarding the assaults in Regensburg nobody doubts that it concerns "shameful and shameful deeds", which had to be punished and prevented in the future; however, the "degree of media manipulation" is remarkable, so the authoress Lucetta Scaraffia, historian and member of the national Italian bioethics.
"The habit of describing the Catholic Church as the source of all evil is already part of everyday experience and prepares public opinion to consider this normal," writes Scaraffia.
In an interview with Bayerischer Rundfunk (Bavarian Radio), Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis also said: "You like to go to church and that's a real treat."
In addition, she pointed out that in her youth, "beatings were a normal pedagogical tool" for "coping with cheeky children like me".
It would find it unfair to apply today ’ s standards to past decades, because the world has changed.
Pope George Ratzinger also often appeared in connection with the reports of cases of abuse.
Author and historian Michael Hesemann, who with Ratzinger wrote the volume "My Brother the Pope" (translated into 12 languages), is completely wrong.
"I have to defend Georg Ratzinger", says Hesemann, "because all this had nothing to do with him", he assesses the results of the final report.
What exactly is written in the 440 page report, which the lawyer Ulrich Weber commissioned by the diocese of Regensburg with the Enlightenment has submitted?
A total of 547 Regensburger Domspatzen were sexually abused between 1945 and the beginning of the 1990s, "with high plausibility", victims of attacks, 67 Domspatzen.
The final report on Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994, states: "In summary, it can be said that R. the Domkapellmeister often used forms of physical and psychological violence.
Especially with high emotionality, the punishment for the students could also be more severe.
Nevertheless, in contrast to numerous other accused persons, it is noticeable that many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore in numerous cases, despite violence, even associate him with positive memories. "
In an interview, Hesemann explains why the final report on the abuse scandal involving the Regensburger Domspatzen (Regensburg Cathedral sparrows) exonerates Georg Ratzinger in his opinion.
Mr. Hesemann, the 440 pages "Report on the" Incidents of Exercising Violence on Responsible Persons at the Regensburger Domspatzen "gives a contradictory picture of cathedral music director Georg Ratzinger.
On the one hand, many students emphasize his "humanity".
On the other hand, he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist, who often became palpable when a cathedral sparrow did not perform top.
How do you view this final report as his biographer?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble to read the entire 440-page report from beginning to end, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger appears in it at all.
Only eight pages are devoted to him and he is clearly acquitted of any suspicion of complicity or complicity in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The excesses of violence at the pre-school also occurred outside his sphere of influence.
One can only accuse him of having learned of it too late or of not having taken the first hints seriously enough.
The Domspatzengymnasium, on which he worked, was felt by practically all interviewees as - so literally - "redemption", "heaven" and "better world".
The vast majority of his students, Georg Ratzinger, also gave an excellent certificate, describing him as "warm-hearted", "popular", "sincere", "competent" and "understanding", as an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly provided the boys with cakes, biscuits and sweets and was "always surrounded by bunches of children".
Only a minority complains about his perfectionism and high emotionality, which sometimes led to outbursts of anger.
The fact that he not only banged with chairs and threw the key ring on the floor, but also slapped and pulled too cheeky boys by the hair or ears, he himself has already admitted years ago, deeply regretted and apologized for it.
In order to save his honor, however, it must be said that such methods of education were widespread in the 1960s and 1970s, among parents and teachers alike.
Do you still know such disciplinary methods?
Of course, I think every one of us who was born before 1968.
I too experienced this in a secular school, a state high school.
Compared with what this report is actually about, namely the appalling sexual abuse and the excesses of violence at pre-school level, these are, of course, trifles.
One wonders whether it is not rather to do with his fame and his role as brother of Benedict XVI that many media have fallen on him.
Many who have never understood the Bavarian Pope are still working diligently on it.
But the truth is that the report discharges Georg Ratzinger in every respect.
In connection with the report, a great deal was reported in the media on the subject of abuse by the Regensburger Domspatzen.
Is Georg Ratzinger also accused in the final report of any involvement or complicity with regard to sexual abuse?
Michael Hesemann: Absolutely no.
None of the 67 victims of sexual assault claim to have entrusted themselves to the cathedral music director.
Not even the parents were initiated.
"I never dared to talk to my father or my mother about it," one of the people concerned said on behalf of the others, "I was very embarrassed."
The real problem in elucidating sexual abuse has been, and still is, that most victims remain silent out of shame.
If they did not even entrust themselves to parents and siblings, then certainly not to a choirmaster who would have been a professional colleague of the perpetrators.
How do the Domspatzen assess Ratzinger's pupils' role with regard to the cases of abuse?
Michael Hesemann: An interrogated pupil put it like this: "Concerning sexual abuse... I see... no case in which he (Georg Ratzinger) would have had timely knowledge and could have stopped the respective perpetrator.
I think it is... also really absurd to assume that he of all people... boys have opened up more insistently or more clearly or even sooner than to their parents, boarders, teachers of trust, etc.
That you talk to him about sex... - unthinkable. "
Thus, the report comes to the very clear conclusion: "The fact that pupils and / or their environment were entrusted to him beforehand could not be confirmed in the course of the investigation".
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger must therefore be acquitted of all complicity.
He cannot therefore be accused of not having prevented him or of having brought him to trial.
There is therefore no reason to associate his good name with these vile crimes, as has unfortunately happened in some cases.
In the media there was much to be read of "excesses of violence" by the Regensburger Domspatzen.
The former cathedral music director Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report of "looking away".
Does he have to live with this reproach?
Michael Hesemann: That is the big problem, that in the reporting everything was mixed up to a huge mélange of sexual abuse and violence and somewhere, right in the middle, Georg Ratzinger.
Yet that, in turn, is an abuse of the report.
There is a clear separation: between the pre-school and the gymnasium of the Domspatzen, between sexual abuse and excesses of violence and, let us say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the time since 1945, thus also from four decades, in which Georg Ratzinger was not choirmaster of the Domspatzen.
All this terrible beating-pedagogy, the cases in which boys were downright harassed and maltreated by sadistic teachers and suffered terribly from it, all happened at the pre-school in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where really scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them, because he only saw the boys when they were already at the Domspatzengymnasium.
At that time, as most witnesses point out, the subject of "preschool" was taboo.
One was only happy to have escaped her and enjoyed the so much better treatment and for many even "paradisiacal" conditions.
What was different at the Domspatzengymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but no sadistic violence.
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger, in whom the report comes to the conclusion that "many victims appreciated R. 's general humanity and therefore in numerous cases, despite violence, even associate him with positive memories".
All that remains is the reproach of having looked the other way.
But despite all efforts, the report could only define two periods in which it was told about the conditions in the pre-school.
The first time in 1970 / 71, when he was just starting to establish himself and didn ’ t want to hear anything about the events at a school where he was not active and responsible (according to the witness), and then again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears to the conditions?
Michael Hesemann: No, because in 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
In it he points out to this, "that in the pre-school the caning is still practiced".
Already in view of the danger of negative press releases he recommended urgent intervention.
That was, of course, at a time when there was legal clarity, when corporal punishment had long been prohibited in Bavaria.
Before that, they happened in a legal grey area, as we all know.
It was difficult for him to estimate where the people affected had perhaps exaggerated or dramatised and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can't say he always looked the other way.
That is simply not true.
It was not until 1980 that caning at schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply the current pedagogical standards to the time.
How do you see this?
Michael Hesemann: We historians talk about the "pitfall of anachronism", that is the danger to evaluate the past according to today's moral standards.
The princess is right.
But, of course, this does not apply to sexual abuse, which has always been abominable, nor to the atrocities and violence committed in pre-school against innocent children ’ s souls, which goes far beyond what was common at the time.
That is all terrible and I am glad that it is finally being worked through.
At the same time, however, I must defend Georg Ratzinger, because none of this had anything to do with him.
His means of disciplining and punishing, i.e. slapping his face and pulling his hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When physical punishment was then banned, he also adhered strictly to it.
What image of his time in Regensburg did Georg Ratzinger reproduce in the conversations with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Was the issue of caning also raised?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book deals with the life of his brother Joseph, i.e. Pope Benedict XVI, tells from his perspective that the Domspatzen only played a minor role.
Nevertheless, I do not at all conceal the fact that he led a strict regime there.
But this also has to be said: without this perfectionism, without the demand for unconditional discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to form an institution of world-class status out of the Regensburger Domspatzen (Regensburg Cathedral Sparrows), which until then was rather nationally known, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition, which went on tour twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With biscuits and sweets alone, you don ’ t make recalcitrant boys into great singers, and before every success, no matter in which field, you always have discipline, passion and self-conquest.
What kind of person did you see Georg Ratzinger as when talking about your book?
Michael Hesemann: Through the work on the book and beyond, I have really got to know Georg Ratzinger very well and have experienced him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, kind, deeply believing and kind person, of whom one cannot imagine that he could harm even one fly.
I regularly hear how many former Domspatzen still keep in contact with him today, 23 years after his retirement, visit him, read to him - he is almost blind - and treat him as a member of their family.
Those who to this day do not forgive him that he was once strict with them are therefore clearly in the minority.
Most Domspatzen are grateful to him today for having enriched their lives and brought them closer to the world of music.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher - a strict father, of course, that may be - but also a lovable respecter to whom they still look up today and to whom they almost adore.
And please, once again very clearly: all he is accused of is educational methods, which were the order of the day at the time.
We can be glad that we have overcome this time long ago.
But it is highly unfair to make a man a media scapegoat just because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother.
The evil intention behind it is all too obvious.
The report that has just been published discharges him.
Now the decency would order to leave a 93-year-old man, who has earned great merits and without whom outside Bavaria and perhaps still Germany probably no one would know the Regensburger Domspatzen, finally in peace.
